prefLabel.en: Prize Papers: Relation between object and place

en: The vocabulary "relation between object and place" collects the concepts describing which role a place had in an event an object was involved in or was supposed to be involved in.

prefLabel.de: Prize Papers: Beziehung zwischen Akteur und Akteur
prefLabel.en: Prize Papers: Relation between actor and actor

en: The vocabulary "relation between actor and actor" collects the concepts developed to describe the (communicative) connections between actors found in the Prize Papers Collection as identified and recorded by the Prize Papers Project.
The vocabulary of "place" collects all concepts referring to geophysical locations. They consist of a name and (usually) geographic coordinates.

The "actor" vocabulary collects all actors identified by the Prize Papers Project in Prize Papers collection. An “actor” may either be an individual person, or an institution or group of people acting in their own right as a unity

The vocabulary "document court classification" contains the concepts referring to the status of the objects in the collection in context of the Prize trial, its paperwork as well as its (subsequent) archiving. It is based on a classification developed at The National Archives (London).

The vocabulary of "ethnicity" comprises concepts of group affiliation as identified by the Prize Papers Project in the Prize Papers Collection. These group affiliations can be based on several, and eventually multiple factors such as topoi of shared (regional) origin and/or "heimat"; topoi of a shared history, myth of foundation, and/or fate; a common religious ancestry and/ or (minority) language. In contrast to (pure) religious affiliation for example, ethnic affiliation carries a strong hereditary/ ancestral moment. – or: In contrast to religious affiliation, ethnic affiliation juxtaposes affiliation by ancestry and heritage rather than the spiritual aspect of religious faith.
The vocabulary of "format" collects all concepts referring to the dimension of writing surfaces.

The vocabulary of "subject" collects all concepts developed in the Prize Papers Project to identify, differentiate, and discriminate fields of interests objects in the collection may hold information of.

en:
The vocabulary of "journey type" represents the systematization of ship movements in the context of the prize business documented by the Prize Papers collection. This system references spatially to the locations of events ships were involved in, and functionally to the meaning said events had in shipping and prize taking business.
The concepts are also used to identify the captured and capturing ships of a capture in the data model.
The vocabulary of "lading unit" collects contemporary concepts used in the documents of the Prize Papers Collection to count and measure actors and objects on board a ship.

prefLabel.de: Prize Papers: Beziehung zwischen Reise und Akteur
prefLabel.en: Prize Papers: Relation between journey and actor

en: The vocabulary "relation between journey and actor" collects the concepts describing the role of an identified actor. In this case actors can only be persons, on board of a ship during a specific journey
The vocabulary "ship class" collects the concepts categorizing types of ships according to their physical features or function.

prefLabel.de: Arbeitsgemeinschaft Alte Drucke beim GBV und SWB

de: Gattungsbegriffe der Arbeitsgemeinschaft Alte Drucke beim GBV und SWB

en: The vocabulary of "lading type" collects concepts of actors and objects on board of a ship on a journey. With regard to actors, these concepts identify the function these actors had during that journey. Artefacts are not differentiated according to function (i.e. cargo or stock).
The vocabulary "ruling authority" contains the concepts of power constellations to which actors are subjected to as identified by the Prize Papers Project.
The vocabulary "material of document" collects all terms referring to substrate components a document is made of.
The vocabulary "court process decision type" collects the concepts defining the quality a verdict could assume within prize court jurisdiction.

en: "The PARTAGE PLUS VOCABULARY is a structured multilingual controlled vocabulary. It consists of components for the enrichment of metadata created for cultural heritage objects relating to Art Nouveau aesthetic production encompassing the visual arts, crafts and architecture, - referencing to and mainly based on the Art & Architecture Thesaurus of the Getty Research Institute. The controlled vocabulary contains 705 concepts represented by labels in 16 languages for the indexing of cultural heritage metadata, referring to object/work types; techniques; materials; actor roles and Art Nouveau style specific differentiation. (...) The vocabulary is available for free reuse." (http://www.partage-plus.eu/files/inlineattachments/vocab/Partage-Plus-Use-of-Vocabulary.pdf)
